<dl id="n03020d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03020d">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03020d"> 20(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 3 lights in valley <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03020d"><li>FW 22.27 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n03020d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n03020d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03020d">MS BL 47472-27</ms> </li><li>JJA 44:130 <a name="ad2" href="../../ff/fdra/ada.htm#ad2">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/ad2.htm#n03020d">Draft: I.1&sect;2.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The writer of <font color="green">[an ancient Irish]</font> manuscript says that &ldquo;the First Order <font color="green">[of Irish saints]</font> was most holy, the Second Order holier, and the Third holy. The First glowed like the sun in the fervour of their charity; the Second cast a pale radiance like the moon; the Third shone like the aurora. These Three Orders the blessed Patrick foreknew, enlightened by heavenly wisdom, when in prophetic vision he saw at first all Ireland ablaze, and afterwards only the mountains on fire; and at last saw <mark>lamps lit in the valleys</mark>.&rdquo; <small> J.M. Flood, <a name="JMFI" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JMFI"><cite title="source">Ireland: Its Saints and Scholars</cite></a> (n.d) 43-4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
